<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Savings study at odds with official figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST BRITONS say they have not been saving more in the past two years,
according to a survey by Mintel, the market research company.
Official statistics have shown an increase in the savings ratio, which
measures savings as a percentage of total personal disposable income, but 70
per cent of those interviewed by Mintel say they have not started to save
more in the past year or two.
Some economists believe that the end of the house-price surge will have
encouraged people to build up financial assets. Previously, they were able
to rely on rising house prices for increases in their wealth. However, only
10 per cent of those interviewed agree with the statement: 'The end of the
house-price boom has given me the incentive to start saving again'. And 83
per cent disagree.
Of those who are saving, Mintel says that 49.9 per cent of their assets are
in the form of life assurance and pensions, compared with 32.6 per cent in
1979. The proportion of assets held in the form of securities and unit
trusts has fallen from 14.4 per cent to 11.8 per cent over the same period.
The report identifies five types of saver. The first is the 'empty-nester
investor', mainly men aged 45 to 64, living in London and the south-east and
earning more than Pounds 20,000 a year. They have high levels of ownership
of personal equity plans, pensions and high-interest accounts.
'Nervous non-savers' are predominantly women aged over 55 and earning less
than Pounds 8,000 a year. These people typically own life assurance
purchased from a salesman, but find it difficult to save.
'Careful consumers and safe savers' are often women aged over 45 and earning
less than Pounds 11,000. They save through building societies, but feel that
shares are too risky.
'No wealth, no worries' is how Mintel describes the fourth group. These
people tend to be men and single women aged under 34 who have bank or
building society accounts which allow them to withdraw money through
automated teller machines. But they feel they are no good at saving, and
like to leave financial matters to someone else.
'Tangled savers', Mintel says, are people aged between 25 and 44 who earn
more than Pounds 11,000. Although they own a wide range of investment
products, they feel they are no good at saving.
The Mintel analysis was based on a sample of 25,000 people studied by the
British Market Research Bureau.
National Savings inflow rose sharply in the nine months from March to
December, according to figures released yesterday. The total inflow of
savings was Pounds 1.88bn, up from Pounds 1.05bn in the same period a year
earlier.
Savings - Is it A British Problem? Mintel International Group, 18-19 Long
Lane, London EC1A 9HE.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
