<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Pre-Christmas sales dismay retailers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VOLUME of pre-Christmas sales was sharply lower than retailers had hoped
for, in spite of heavy price discounting, while retail sales this month are
expected to fall for the first time since June last year.
This is the message from the latest Distributive Trades Survey conducted by
the Confederation of British Industry.
Retailers report that sales in December were fractionally up on a year ago,
but by much less than had been anticipated in the November survey.
The heavy price discounting seen throughout last month did not produce the
hoped-for boost, said Mr Nigel Whittaker, survey panel chairman.
Moreover, what sales there were involved consumers moving their purchases
forward from this month to December. 'As a result, retailers now expect
sales to weaken in January,' Mr Whittaker said.
The survey, conducted between December 16 and January 8, shows that 39 per
cent of retailers reported sales last month above the level of the same
month the year before, while 34 per cent reported lower sales. This gives a
positive balance of 5 percentage points, compared with a positive balance of
28 points for those who had been expecting higher sales last month.
Taking the distributive trades as a whole, covering 15,000 outlets in the
wholesale and motor trades as well as retailers, the picture was even more
gloomy. Overall, 31 per cent of traders reported higher sales in December
than the year before, with 38 per cent reporting lower sales. The negative
percentage balance of 7 points comes after three successive months in which
sales were reported to be up on the same month the previous year.
Among retailers, grocers and chemists reported continued year-on-year growth
in sales, while off-licences and retailers of footwear and durable goods all
reported sales volumes below those of the previous year. Clothing retailers
experienced a particularly sharp turn-around after two months of sales
growth.
Only 25 per cent of retailers expect sales this month to be higher than a
year ago, with 31 per cent expecting lower sales. This balance of
expectations suggests that overall sales will fall this month for the first
time since June. Off-licences and booksellers expect the largest declines.
Modest sales growth and falling expectations for trade this month have led
retailers to cut back both on stocks and on wholesale orders. A higher
proportion of retailers reported placing lower orders with suppliers last
month than in December the previous year, and similar numbers expect to
reduce orders this month.
Lower orders from retailers have already bitten into wholesale sales, which
have slipped below the depressed levels of December 1990 after three months
of year-on-year growth. A total of 27 per cent of wholesalers report higher
sales last month compared with 37 per cent reporting lower sales. The
negative balance of 10 points remains above the low of a negative balance of
48 percentage points in February.
Sales in the motor trades remain poor and are expected to deteriorate again
this month, although at a slower rate than last year. Most report lower
sales last month, although the negative balance of 47 points is an
improvement on the low of a negative balance of 89 points in May of last
year, while sellers of parts and accessories report sales last month up on
the year before.
