<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Political fears hit north-west businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent and EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS confidence in north-west England is being adversely affected by
political and economic uncertainty, as well as the recession, according to
the 1991 fourth-quarter survey of nine chambers of commerce in the region.
Some manufacturers reported signs of improving exports, but domestic orders
continued to reflect low demand. But the gap between those reporting a drop
in home orders and those experiencing a rise was the smallest for the year.
Confidence fell from the third-quarter peak, with companies expecting some
upturn in the second half of this year, but from a very low base and with no
evidence or experience yet apparent to back up this belief. The survey
covered 279 manufacturers employing 63,000 people and 218 service-sector
companies with 41,000 employees, with the bulk of companies employing fewer
than 200 people each.
London's service sector is showing faint signs that it is emerging from
recession, according to the latest quarterly economic survey from the
capital's chamber of commerce and industry, Edward Balls writes.
Yet there is little evidence in the survey to suggest that a strong overall
recovery is under way, cautioned the chamber of commerce: 'The signs of
recovery in the service sector are still faint while the manufacturing
sector is still very much in recession.'
The survey of 250 companies with a total of 250,000 employees reveals that a
net positive balance of 3 percentage points of service companies are
increasing their domestic activity, against a negative balance of 23
percentage points in the previous survey.
Manufacturers remain depressed, with output falling particularly sharply in
export markets. Domestic orders remain depressed, with a negative balance of
5 percentage points reporting higher orders, against a negative balance of
18 points last survey.
</TEXT>
