<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Lords threat to council tax timing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S aim of enacting the Council Tax Bill by the end of next
month could be at risk unless ministers make concessions to strong
cross-party alliances among peers who tomorrow start detailed discussion of
the bill.
Ensuring the legislation is completed within the next six weeks or so is
critical in terms of election timing, especially with renewed emphasis on
the possibility of an April poll.
The Tories insist that the poll tax will be abolished from April next year,
and failing to secure the bill to introduce its replacement would seriously
undermine this commitment.
Tory backbench peers have already proposed changes to the bill to improve
the position of tenants in tied cottages. Changes to get a better deal for
the disabled have attracted support from both sides of the Lords. Tory and
Labour peers have also privately been voicing concern about the speed with
which the bill was dealt with in the Commons.
There are signs that peers will want to compensate for the lack of committee
discussion among MPs on the interaction of social security benefits with the
council tax discount system.
There are also peers linked with interested pressure groups and charities
who are concerned their organisations did not have enough time to study the
proposals and put forward changes in the time the bill could have been
amended by the Commons.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour's local government spokesman, said: 'It is vital
that the House of Lords is able to provide detailed scrutiny of this
legislation because of the government's draconian tactics in the Commons.
'The government's business managers will be desperate to bulldoze this
through. In the interests of parliamentary democracy and local taxpayers,
the Lords should ensure a full discussion of all these important issues.'
</TEXT>
