<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Tories study fresh child care tax move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is examining new tax relief measures aimed at encouraging
small and medium-sized employers to participate in child care schemes
outside the workplace, it emerged yesterday.
Also under consideration are special payments or vouchers to help working
mothers pay for creches and other child care during working hours.
Budget reforms three years ago introduced tax relief on the use of
employer-provided nurseries. That could now be extended to registered
nurseries out of the workplace, allowing employees in companies that employ
too few people with small children for an in-house creche to benefit if
their employers contribute to local schemes.
Womens' interest groups are also pressing for allowances payable to mothers
whose jobs are jeopardised by the need to care for children in the
afternoons or holidays. They suggest that a payment or voucher worth about
Pounds 5 a week could help at a cost to the Treasury of as little as Pounds
10m a year.
Mrs Angela Rumbold, Home Office minister responsible for womens' issues, is
expected to see Mr John Major, the prime minister today or tomorrow to press
for measures to raise the Tories' electoral appeal to women. She said last
night: 'I believe that my Treasury colleagues are well aware of the
political importance of making sure working women are not disgruntled.'
Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, yesterday confirmed that the
government was looking again at homelessness among the mentally ill. He said
most of those released from long-term institutions over the past few years
had found accommodation.
</TEXT>
