<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Zhelev wins Bulgarian election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SOFIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REFORMIST Zhelyu Zhelev won Bulgaria's first presidential election
yesterday, according to unofficial results, ending communist hopes of
clinging to a slice of power, Reuter reports from Sofia.
His victory consolidates power in the hands of the Union of Democratic
Forces (UDF), which now controls the presidency as well as the government it
formed after winning a general election last October. But the margin of
victory was relatively narrow in both cases, reflecting the lingering appeal
of communist-inspired policies in the Balkan country of 8.5m people.
According to unofficial results which the state news agency BTA said would
be confirmed, Mr Zhelev was given about 54 per cent of the vote, edging out
Mr Velko Valkanov, his rival backed by the socialists (former communists),
who got about 46 per cent.
</TEXT>
