FT  20 JAN 92 / BAe faces Pounds 80m claim by Asda over property deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH AEROSPACE, the troubled industrial combine, faces an Pounds 80m
claim from Asda, the supermarket group, arising from an ill-starred property
joint venture.
BAe also confirmed yesterday that Mr Dudley Eustace, its finance director,
was leaving the company. The parting was 'amicable', it said, but would make
no further comment. A formal announcement is due today.
Mr Eustace has been BAe's finance director throughout recent turbulent
events surrounding the company, including the removal from the chairmanship
of Sir Roland Smith, his replacement on a temporary basis by Sir Graham Day
and the restructuring of top management under Sir Graham in December.
The company has been striving to repair the damage to its City image wrought
by the failure of last year's Pounds 432m rights issue and heavy fall in
profits. The rights issue collapsed, leaving 95 per cent with the
underwriters.
BAe is involved in what are described as 'delicate discussions' with Asda,
which is calling in a property value indemnity originally signed with
Arlington Development Properties just before the property group was acquired
by BAe.
At last week's meeting to announce an interim loss of Pounds 68.8m, Mr
Archie Norman, Asda's recently appointed chief executive, told a City
analyst that the group had full indemnity cover on this venture. 'Our
lawyers say that the indemnity agreement is absolutely rock solid,' Asda
said yesterday. The agreement concerns Burwood House Group, a 50 per cent
jointly owned operation formed in 1989, into which Asda put 34 stores then
valued at Pounds 350m and Arlington some Pounds 75m of property interests.
The indemnity provided that BAe would be liable for any shortfall on
valuation of Arlington's Burwood assets on December 31 1990, and it is on
this liability that Asda is now basing its call for Pounds 80m. The
valuation, carried out by Debenham Tewson &amp; Chinnocks, was deferred by
agreement until last month, but was based on values as at December 1990.
'We did them a big favour,' commented one Asda executive. 'The shortfall at
December 1991 would have been much greater.'
The discussions between the joint owners of Burwood House appear to be
limited to the precise figure of Aerospace's obligation rather than
presenting any challenge to the indemnity itself.
The surfacing of widely predicted losses on the Burwood House deal will
inflict a further blow on BAe's reputation. The Pounds 278m purchase of
Arlington in 1989, at the peak of the property boom, was strongly
crit-icised in the City at the time.
