<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When American steel millionaire Lawrence Thaw and his wife Peggy toured
India in 1939 they went in a huge motor caravan, taking with them a leading
cinematographer to record the event on 35 mm Magnacolor film stock. The
resulting holiday films provide the material for today's Voices From The
Past (7.40 BBC2). Horizon, which follows at 8.10, tells the story of
Buckminsterfullerene, a type of carbon discovered by two physicists in 1990
and named after the architect who was so keen on geodesic domes.
It seems that the discovery 'revolutionised chemistry overnight', and
industrialists are now talking about new polymers, lubricants, and
nano-technology, but the two physicists are wondering whether
Buckminsterfullerene is the solution to one of the great mysteries of
astronomy.
The second programme in the four-part Falklands War (9.00 C4) deals with the
sailing of the task force and the sinking of the General Belgrano. BBC2
screens the last part of its drama Goodbye Cruel World (9.00) about 'Way's
Disease' and the politics of medical charities. Panorama (9.30 BBC1)
investigates the disappearance of long-stay geriatric beds from NHS
hospitals.
</TEXT>
