<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 92 / Growth in managers' pay slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INCREASES in total pay for managers slowed last year to an average of less
than 10 per cent, according to a pay index from the Noble Lowndes group of
management consultants and actuaries.
The index includes the value of benefits such as cars and pensions as well
as salaries and bonuses. It is based on the group's regular pay surveys, and
is calculated each quarter for the Financial Times.
The latest survey, which covered 5,304 executives in 417 companies in the
UK, shows that on January 1 the average for managers of all ranks was Pounds
75,794, 9.3 per cent up on the Pounds 69,345 average at the beginning of
1991. The corresponding increase in 1990-91 was 13.8 per cent. Although the
total rose, the bonus element fell slightly last year to Pounds 4,290
compared with Pounds 4,369 in 1990.
In general, the 'all-ranks' rises were lowest in companies with sales
turnovers of less than Pounds 100m, where they averaged just over 8.5 per
cent. The corresponding figures for larger companies were 10.2 per cent for
those in the Pounds 101m-Pounds 600m range and 10 per cent for those
turnovers of Pounds 600m or more.
Further information from Mr Brian Barnes, PO Box 144, Norfolk House,
Wellesley Rd, Croydon CR9 3EB.
</TEXT>
