<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): IBM share price recovery aids
Dow rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A VOLATILE day for US stock markets ended on a positive note yesterday as
higher bond prices and a recovery in IBM's share price following a
disappointing set of quarterly earnings lifted the Dow Jones Industrial
Average to another record high, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow was up 15.43 at 3,264.98. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended up 0.64 at 418.85, while the Nasdaq composite of
over-the-counter stocks slipped 0.60 at 626.74. NYSE turnover was 286m
shares, and rises marginally outpaced declines by 905 to 814.
There were a few titbits of fresh economic news to give the market
direction. The announcement of a 0.2 per cent reduction in December
industrial production, and a decline in the University of Michigan's
consumer sentiment index for early January should have injected a sour note
at the end of what was generally a good week for stocks. The market,
however, was able to draw comfort from a rise in bond prices, which prompted
a much-needed reduction in long-term interest rates.
Most eyes were on IBM, which announced a fourth-quarter loss of Dollars
1.38bn after taking a slightly bigger-than-expected charge of Dollars 3.4bn
to cover restructuring costs. The stock fell more than Dollars 2 on the
release of the figures, which were deemed by analysts to be disappointing,
but later recovered to end Dollars 1 1/4 higher at Dollars 96 3/4 in
turnover of 2.6m shares as investors reacted positively to reports of upbeat
comments from IBM's management.
Other big computer stocks were mixed in the wake of IBM's results. Compaq
rose Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 33 3/4 , Digital Equipment fell Dollars 1 3/4
to Dollars 53, Hewlett-Packard slipped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 62, Unisys
held firm at Dollars 5 1/2 and Motorola rose Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 79 7/8
.
Reebok climbed Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 31 1/2 on earnings in line with
market estimates. Reebok had been heavily sold on Thursday in anticipation
of poor results.
Citicorp ran into profit-taking for the second day running, dropping Dollars
 1/4 to Dollars 14 5/8 in turnover of 3.4m shares. The stock has enjoyed a
remarkable ride in recent days, buoyed up by heavy demand from investors who
believe the worst may be over for the troubled banking group. Since
Thursday, however, some investors have been taking profits on the assumption
that Citicorp's rally may have stalled for now.
On the over-the-counter market, Apple jumped Dollars 2 to Dollars 64 3/4 on
news of fiscal first quarter net income of Dollars 1.36 a share, up from
Dollars 1.28 a share a year ago.
Canada
TORONTO stock prices closed mixed in heavy trading.
According to preliminary figures, the composite index fell 7.67 points, or
0.21 per cent, to close at 3,658.29, but advancing issues outnumbered
declines 380 to 252. Volume was 34.941m shares, down from yesterday's
39.983m shares, and trading value fell to CDollars 456.8m from CDollars
487.3m. The index finished the hectic week up about 65 points, or about 1.8
per cent.
Euro-Nevada fell  1/4 to 18 3/4 on news it will issue 1.5m special
convertible warrants at CDollars 18.75 a warrant. Ocelot Industries was
unchanged at 11 7/8 . The company said it will sell to an underwiting group
4m special warrants at CDollars 11.50 a warrant, each of which is
exercisable for one common share.
