<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 92 / Lottery fails to win government support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government put a national lottery firmly on the backburner yesterday by
declining to back a bill even though it saw 'attractions' in the idea.
It pledged to 'examine further' issues that a lottery would raise. Mr Peter
Lloyd, a junior Home Office minister, said: 'We shall put that work in hand
immediately and announce our conclusions as soon as possible.'
Without government support, fewer than 100 MPs voted for the bill in a
closure motion. The measure therefore stands only a slender chance of
becoming law.
Mr Ivan Lawrence, Conservative MP for Burton, who introduced the bill, said
its aim was 'nothing less than to raise the quality of life in Britain to
even higher levels'. He added that Albania was the only other European
country not to have a lottery and reminded MPs that lottery money had paid
for construction of the British Museum.
Mr Terry Dicks, Conservative MP for Hayes and Harlington, said he would
oppose the bill unless proposals to use some of the proceeds to support the
arts were withdrawn.
The Rev Ian Paisley, Democratic Unionist leader, said: 'We have enough
gambling outlets without the government going into gambling sponsorship.'
Ladbroke is offering 2-1 against a national lottery bill being passed in the
lifetime of the next government.
</TEXT>
