FT  18 JAN 92 / Brazil's Collor sacks two ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Fernando Collor of Brazil last night sacked two of his ministers,
replacing them with federal deputies in an attempt to reduce his political
isolation, writes Christina Lamb from Rio de Janeiro.
The surprise move came after the government failed to secure Congressional
approval of emergency legislation to increase social security payments to
fund rises in pensions.
The two new ministers are both from parties which support the government but
voted against it this week.
Mr Ricardo Fiuza, the new minister for social affairs, and Mr Reinold
Stefanis, the new labour minister, both said Mr Collor had explained that he
needed to increase his base in Congress.
They will now have the task of trying to find the Dollars 10bn (Pounds
5.5bn) which the goverment says it needs for the increased pensions.
The International Monetary Fund has delayed a decision over the approval of
a Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.1bn) loan to Brazil.
Brazilian officials said the meeting, due to take place next Wednesday, has
been delayed because it would clash with a meeting of heads of state from
the former Soviet Union which Mr Michel Camdessus, the IMF chief, is to
attend.
