<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 92 / Finance and the Family (Briefcase): A prized inheritance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
YEARS ago my wife's father bought premium bonds (Pounds 25 each) for our
three children. With their agreement the bonds were replaced by Pounds 75
worth in my name, to achieve equal benefit from any large win, which is what
their grandfather would have wished.
Now we see that a win could be liable to inheritance tax. Can the bonds, or
replacements in joint names be put into a trust to benefit only the
children, with access to any income?
From what you say it seems that the bonds are already held on trust for the
three children as joint beneficiaries. If so this should be confirmed in a
declaration of trust made by the bond-holders. If not, they can be put into
trust, but only with the agreement of anyone who might be entitled to a
specified bond, or its winnings. There should be no income from such a
trust.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
