<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 92 / International Company News: Inland Steel turns in record
loss of Dollars 275.1m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INLAND Steel reported its largest ever annual loss in 1991 totalling Dollars
275.1m, or Dollars 9.88 per share.
The results, already hit by low steel prices and poor demand for consumer
durables, were further depressed by a Dollars 215m restructuring charge
relating to plant closures and about 3,500 jobs cuts. The workforce
reduction will take place over several years.
Before the restructuring provision, the company's net loss last year was
Dollars 110m, or Dollars 4.55 per share, compared with a net loss of Dollars
20.6m, or Dollars 1.41, in 1990. Sales fell by 12 per cent to Dollars 3.4bn
from Dollars 3.87bn in 1990.
For the fourth quarter, when the charge was taken, Inland reported a net
loss of Dollars 191.3m, or Dollars 6.44. Before the charge, the loss had
been Dollars 26.2m, or Dollars 1.11, against losses of Dollars 57.1m, or
Dollars 2.05 per share, a year ago.
Mr Frank Luerssen, Inland's chairman, said the company's restructuring and a
modernisation programme should allow it to benefit from steel's next upturn.
But, he said, 'we have no illusions that the months ahead are going to be
anything but difficult. The outlook for steel orders, particularly from the
automobile industry, remains weak.'
</TEXT>
